1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:15,000
So what I'm going to do first is just do a little introduction for the tape and then we'll start talking.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:21,000
And we'll take it from there and anytime you want to stop, we can stop for a second.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Okay, so today is August the 14th, 2013.

5
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:34,000
Speaking is David Klein from the History Department at Virginia Tech in Blacksburg.

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:39,000
Also working for the Southern Oral History Program at UNC Chapel Hill.

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Today I have the honor of interviewing Kay Tillo here in Louisville, Kentucky.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Behind the camera is John Bishop of Media Generation and UCLA.

9
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:52,000
And I think that's everything.

10
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Reading the paper on the couch in the morning.

11
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:04,000
And we're back here in the lovely home of Kay and Walter Tillo, so hello to Walter as well.

12
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Thank you for having us back here.

13
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
So if we could just start, if you could just introduce yourself.

14
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Your age where you were born and that would be great and then we'll have a conversation.

15
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:28,000
My name is Kay Tillo and I was born in Paduca, Kentucky in 1942.

16
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:35,000
And my parents lived in Matropolis, Illinois, which was across the river from Paduca.

17
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
Paduca was the closest hospital.

18
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:42,000
And I grew up in Matropolis, Illinois.

19
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:50,000
And if you could tell us a little bit about your upbringing and if you see anything sort of in the way that you are raised,

20
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:58,000
the family that you are from that may have caused you to become involved in the movement in later years.

21
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:05,000
Well, my parents were of modest means.

22
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Both of them were from farm families, of families that had come over from Germany and were eager to get land here.

23
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:24,000
And every German family had a plot of 80 acres.

24
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:31,000
I'm not quite sure how that happened, but that's where my grandparents each lived on a farm.

25
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:35,000
And both of my parents grew up on the farm.

26
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:46,000
And my mom was able to go to Southern Illinois Teachers College and became a teacher.

27
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:54,000
My father had a, he formed and he also had a furniture store.

28
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:01,000
So we lived in the town was very small, 6,000 people and it's still 6,000 people.

29
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:10,000
So Matropolis is just a farmed town and very, very far away from urban centers.

30
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,000
It's like halfway between St. Louis and Memphis.

31
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:19,000
And so the big city is Paduca, which is like 36,000.

32
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:27,000
So I went to grade school and high school there and my parents were involved and active in the church.

33
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:38,000
So I think perhaps one of the things that influenced me most was that we had a Presbyterian minister named Maynard Elthman,

34
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:46,000
who at some point when I was in high school gave me a copy of the book The Wall Between by Anne Brayden.

35
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:53,000
And it was an amazing revelation to me from those narrow confines.

36
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:57,000
My family was not at all political in any way.

37
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:01,000
So I didn't, there had no, you know, my family didn't talk about politics.

38
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:07,000
They talked about morals and education and those were the things in the church that guided them.

39
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:12,000
But this book was eye-opening in terms of what was happening.

40
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:17,000
And what kinds of things did Mrs. Brayden talk about in that and how did that affect you?

41
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Well, she told the story of inequality in Louisville, Kentucky and how they had purchased a home for an African American family

42
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:35,000
because the sellers would not sell it to them.

43
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:42,000
So they purchased the home and that brought this terrible backlash.

44
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
And well, everyone knows the story that the house was bombed.

45
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Carlin and were arrested.

46
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Carlin went to prison, charged with sedition, trying to overthrow the state of Kentucky.

47
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
But Anne wrote very well.

48
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:07,000
So she always, she approached it from kind of for someone who didn't understand any of these things at all.

49
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:18,000
I could understand and very moving about inequality and the need to stand up against what was wrong.

50
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:22,000
So that was had a big influence on me.

51
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:27,000
And that was before I graduated from high school in 1960.

52
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:37,000
So what was your immediate world around you there in Metropolis as far as the demographics, as far as equality?

53
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:41,000
What did you see around you and how did that compare to what you were reading?

54
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:48,000
Well, I remember when the grade schools were integrated there when I was in grade school.

55
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:56,000
And I remember, you know, people being very, very upset about that happening.

56
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:00,000
But for a while, and then it seemed that that was over.

57
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:05,000
But of course the African-American teachers lost their jobs.

58
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:09,000
And I don't know when they were later hired.

59
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:13,000
You know, I'm sure that at some point that was changed too.

60
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:16,000
The high school was integrated.

61
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:22,000
And so, you know, it was not...

62
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:26,000
I think it was like the deep south, but they were certainly prejudiced there.

63
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:32,000
I can remember nominating a young African-American to be the head of the...

64
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,000
What was it? The high-try, some girls club in high school.

65
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:41,000
And the teacher telling me, no, we weren't ready for that.

66
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:45,000
So that was in before 60.

67
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
Very interesting.

68
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And that was that before you would have read the book or...?

69
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
I don't know. I don't know that.

70
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
I can't remember how that fits together.

71
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:01,000
This is probably a difficult question, but do you remember your first sort of over-act?

72
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:05,000
Well, I'm not sure exactly which one was first.

73
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,000
I went to the University of Illinois then.

74
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:17,000
And by that time, you know, I joined the NAACP away from a drop of less,

75
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:21,000
which was easier to do, you know.

76
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:30,000
And I remember, my first picket line was at the University of Illinois against some store

77
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:34,000
that wouldn't hire African-Americans.

78
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:41,000
And I remember being very frightened, but believing it was right, and I was going to do it.

79
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:44,000
And I remember what my sign said.

80
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:48,000
I didn't write it, but someone had given me this sign.

81
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:53,000
It said, in the land of Lincoln discrimination is stinkin'.

82
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:57,000
And not too much happened.

83
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:01,000
I mean, we were kind of be rated on the picket line.

84
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:05,000
But things by that time were beginning to happen in the country.

85
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:10,000
And I just went to the meetings and learned, and we would have reports

86
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:19,000
from people coming from the South who would speak at the meetings and tell some of the stories.

87
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:30,000
And the movement was beginning to have impact all across the country and champagne Illinois as well.

88
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:37,000
And so you talk about students visiting, were there other ways that you were getting your news about what was happening?

89
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Well, depending on what year?

90
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:58,000
In 62, in the summer of 62, I was back in Metropolis, and preparing to go to Ghana on a junior year abroad,

91
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:01,000
which I went in 62.

92
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:10,000
But during that summer before then, I went with the local NAACP, because there were SNCC demonstrations in Carroll,

93
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:14,000
which was about 40 miles away.

94
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:19,000
And we traveled to go, you know, we went to the court hearings.

95
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:28,000
It was a segregated courtroom, and I remember being just amazed at the courage of these people.

96
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:34,000
Mary McCullum was one of the people who was there, and she had a big hurt.

97
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:42,000
She had been cut on her thigh, a huge gash during one of the demonstrations.

98
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:49,000
And just, you know, people were facing such brutality and were so strong.

99
00:09:50,000 --> 00:10:01,000
That was it about the Civil Rights Movement, is that you gained inspiration by these other people who you admired so,

100
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:07,000
and who were really risking everything to stand up for what they believed in.

101
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:10,000
So that had a great impact on me.

102
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:17,000
During that summer, then I went to Ghana, and that was different.

103
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:28,000
W. B. Du Bois was, at the time, he got an emeritus honorary degree there.

104
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:36,000
He had gone there to work on his Pan-African encyclopedia, I think it was.

105
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:40,000
And of course, I didn't know who he was.

106
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:45,000
And all of the students said, you don't know, he's America, you don't know.

107
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:58,000
And I became aware of some of the ignorance and the holes in our education system that here was someone so highly regarded around the world,

108
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:00,000
and I had never heard.

109
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:09,000
So I went to the ceremony where he was given that honorary degree, and he was there with his wife, Shirley Graham Du Bois.

110
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:23,000
And I learned a lot in Africa from Conor Cruzel Brian, was the chancellor of the university, and he had written, took a tanga and back, and all of that story.

111
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:28,000
So I was just becoming aware of the US role in the world.

112
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:37,000
By the time I came back, which was in 63, two things happened on my way back.

113
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:45,000
One was that Du Bois died in August of 63, and the March on Washington.

114
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:53,000
So I came back, and you know, the civil rights movement was in full blossoming.

115
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
You arrived back after the March?

116
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:02,000
Right at the end of August, right afterwards, yes.

117
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:05,000
And so I went back to the University of Illinois.

118
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:15,000
But somewhere along the way I met John Lewis, who came to the University of Illinois, I'm not sure which year that was.

119
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:23,000
Whether that was 63 or whether that was earlier before 62, but it was very impressed.

120
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:42,000
Again, the people who were active in that movement were so inspiring and compelling about what it meant and the value of this cause and this humanity.

121
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:47,000
And I was very moved by him. He had a lot of hair then too.

122
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:52,000
And were the students in a car following what was going on in the US?

123
00:12:52,000 --> 00:13:06,000
Yes. They were. Of course, that was also the time of the missile crisis, which they were all asking me, why?

124
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:13,000
Why, you know, this danger of nuclear war, why is this happening?

125
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:24,000
But I can't remember a lot of discussions about the civil rights movement, but they wanted to know why I had never heard of WB Du Bois.

126
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:34,000
So you get back to campus in 63.

127
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:45,000
Right. And then my NAACP chapter decided to send a delegation to Atlanta during the semester break.

128
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:52,000
And the way I remember it is that we were going to go picket labs.

129
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:59,000
I'm not even sure what labs were. I think it was a restorant or something in Atlanta.

130
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:04,000
And we were going to go down there and see and report back, etc.

131
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:08,000
And I went down with some others from there.

132
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:17,000
As a result of that visit where I remember a discussion with Praithia Hall, who was from Philly.

133
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:24,000
She spoke in Jim Foreman and, you know, lots of other people.

134
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:28,000
And I made the decision that that's what I wanted to do.

135
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:32,000
I couldn't stay in school. I had to go and help.

136
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:38,000
Not that I knew what to do, but that's how compelling the movement was.

137
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:43,000
I remember we went to Hattiesburg.

138
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:50,000
And at the time there were demonstrations over voting there.

139
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:55,000
And Hattiesburg was a very oppressive, violent place.

140
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:01,000
And we were there. Bob Moses had been in jail.

141
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:07,000
And there was a white man also in jail too, from the movement.

142
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:10,000
I can't remember his name.

143
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:16,000
But he had been very badly beaten because they had put him in with the white.

144
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:19,000
It was a segregated jail.

145
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:22,000
And they put him in with the white prisoners.

146
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:28,000
It was really badly beaten. He could hardly be recognized as a human being.

147
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:33,000
And we stayed with a family there in Hattiesburg.

148
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:39,000
And the police, we picketed at the courthouse where they were trying to register.

149
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:51,000
And the police marched in military ranks down the street like they were meeting the enemy.

150
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:58,000
And we remember a gigantic mass meeting there in Hattiesburg with hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of people.

151
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:09,000
So there was this stark comparison between disemilitarized opposition and the violence in the jail.

152
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:20,000
And these people who were not afraid, that was very inspiring that they gave each other courage.

153
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:23,000
And they were not afraid. They had us in their homes.

154
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:26,000
They were under threats of violence.

155
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:32,000
Of course, that was the area where Schwerner, Goodman and Cheney were killed not long after that.

156
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:37,000
But there were hundreds of people.

157
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:44,000
And you could feel that something was moving and shaking and turning.

158
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:52,000
And it was not to be put back in spite of the violent opposition that it faced.

159
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:58,000
Did you identify as a cellar?

160
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:03,000
Or how did you see yourself? And especially as you got into the deeper south from where you were from?

161
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:07,000
Well, I guess I did.

162
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:11,000
I don't know.

163
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:16,000
I was sort of a bit twisted between.

164
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:24,000
But having been born in Kentucky, I claimed Kentucky is where I was born.

165
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:32,000
But then as you got into a place like Hattiesburg, how did that compare to what you had seen growing up?

166
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:38,000
Well, of course there was no movement in Metropolis.

167
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:49,000
I mean, I would say Carol probably could have vied with Hattiesburg for the brutality of the response to the movement.

168
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:52,000
And that was southern Illinois.

169
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:59,000
So, you know, I didn't see Metropolis with a movement there, really.

170
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:07,000
So I'm not sure. And I didn't know any white people in Hattiesburg, other than the people that were in the movement.

171
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:14,000
So you went there just over a school break, but decided that this is where you needed to be.

172
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:19,000
I decided I would go back.

173
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:23,000
That's what I did.

174
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:27,000
People went with the flow at the time.

175
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:45,000
I was young and I certainly didn't have any particular skills to contribute just myself just going down and trying to be there and learn from other people and try to help in whatever way that I could.

176
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:50,000
So what was your first step? How did you find an assignment or what you were going to do?

177
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:56,000
Well, I was with a group that went kind of to these different places.

178
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:06,000
I remember we went to Chapel Hill and we went to Tuskegee where they were preparing that Statenland was there.

179
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:17,000
And they were preparing the Freedom Schools that were going to have in that coming summer. Freedom Summer was in 64.

180
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:29,000
So we kind of went to this place and that place, Chapel Hill, I think there was a student conference and I was at Highlander several times, which is where I met Walter.

181
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:32,000
Oh, that's where you met.

182
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:38,000
Was it at a workshop or what was do you remember with the circumstances?

183
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:41,000
I guess it was a workshop.

184
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:52,000
By that time I was working with a group called the Appalachian Committee for full employment, which was working with miners in Eastern Kentucky.

185
00:19:52,000 --> 00:20:01,000
And the people from SNCC came and we all, you know, people came together and discussed the situation.

186
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:11,000
There were Jim Dumbbrowski being there. He was one of the old, sketch people and I met Carl and Ann.

187
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:22,000
And you know, they kind of weaved throughout all of it. They were really mentors to all of the young people that were coming through the South.

188
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:34,000
They shared the Southern Patriot, which was their newspaper and their skills and their encouragement to everybody that came through.

189
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:51,000
And they were really a tremendous force, I believe, in the rebuilding of the Civil Rights Movement from the early or 30s where the Southern Conference for Human Welfare and I think there was another youth group.

190
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:58,000
And kind of they bridged the gap and kind of reconnected it in that period.

191
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:03,000
So, yeah, how did you, as young people, look at this sort of earlier generation of activists?

192
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:11,000
Well, we had to learn about it because those of us who didn't come from, you know, Walter came from a left background.

193
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:24,000
I came from the farm and I didn't know about anything. So, we had to learn. And of course, Carl and Ann had us reading, you know, reading.

194
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:25,000
What did you read?

195
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:34,000
I tried to understand. Let's see. When did I read Eleanor Flexner's As Century of Struggle on Women?

196
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:57,000
We read a lot of stuff about the Huac. Carl was very strong about the terrible impact of anti-communism and its ability to flatten the progress in the country.

197
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:05,000
And of course, with what he had been through and that whole story about, you know, his life and the sedition charge, et cetera.

198
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:14,000
So, Carl was very strong. I would say they were the big influence on SNCC that the organization would not refuse to be anti-communist.

199
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:24,000
Refused to adopt that kind of liberal anti-communism of Hubert Humphrey.

200
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:32,000
So, the organization that you said that you were working with the VAP Latch and Committee, what were they primarily working on at that time?

201
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:47,000
Well, at the time, I guess the reason I was attracted to it was there was an increasing discussion about economic situation and how important that was in terms of equality.

202
00:22:47,000 --> 00:23:00,000
That, you know, public accommodations was not winning equality and public accommodations would not end the inequality because there was an economic base to it.

203
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:16,000
And of course, I had to learn that too. But I was persuaded by that. And there was a group that was organizing to, there was a group of coal miners in Eastern Kentucky who had tried to revive the country.

204
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:29,000
And they tried to revive the miners' union after it had been broken. And they had been arrested and jailed on a charge of conspiracy.

205
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:45,000
So, there was a legal case and there was kind of a movement around it. And I went there to help. I put out a newspaper called, I don't know, I think it was called Kentucky Jobs with Justice.

206
00:23:45,000 --> 00:24:03,000
And we worked on organizing there. I remember I was there. We marched on Frankfurt with the people who organized from Louisville for, there was a jobs, March on Frankfurt for Jobs in Freedom. And that was March 5th of 1964.

207
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:12,000
And we brought the contingent from the co-feels of Appalachia and joined up with the other people.

208
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:25,000
This is one of the pieces that I think suddenly gets left out often in this story of the civil rights movement especially about, you know, the March on Washington, it was the March on Washington for Jobs in Freedom.

209
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:39,000
The fact that the economic piece from the very beginning was thought of as a part of this civil rights goal. It sounds like you were not early on in the world.

210
00:24:39,000 --> 00:25:02,000
I remember there was a workshop we had at Highlander. Of course Highlander, of course, had been, had participated in the earlier days in the education of those who were the CIO trying to organize workers in the South and trying to organize those agricultural movements black and white together and all.

211
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:28,000
But so we had a conference during the SNCC era on unions. I remember we had someone from the United Electrical workers who came down and talked with us and we had a discussion about, you know, how, what roles should unions play if, you know, in terms of trying to propel justice and equality in the country.

212
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:37,000
So early on you became interested in working in the society. Yeah, I did. Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. What year did you in Walter Me?

213
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:56,000
64, okay. Somewhere in there. Yeah. I'm sort of, I know this is personal, but I'm interested in how it works as a couple in the movement, especially when you're being, you know, there's so much work to be done and you might be pulled to work in different places at different times. And how did that work for you?

214
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:17,000
Well, I don't know. We managed to find a way to put it together. You know, by, by 65 and 66, you know, a lot of people were leaving SNCC.

215
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:36,000
So, you know, Walter worked on that Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party in 64. And in, in, in 66, I believe it was 66. I think we went to work for the electrical workers union.

216
00:26:36,000 --> 00:27:05,000
Both of us. Of course, they sent me one place in him and other, they sent him to Detroit and meet a Pittsburgh, but it still wasn't together. But, after that period of time, you know, the, I think people didn't know exactly what to do in the South. There were different things happening from up to 64.

217
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:18,000
So, in terms of, as SNCC started to change a bit, but it sounds like you were already focused on.

218
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:26,000
Yeah, I was working on, in East Kentucky, you know, for all of 64, basically.

219
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:30,000
And would you catch up and see each other every so often?

220
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:33,000
Yeah, I wasn't so far away.

221
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:41,000
And so then actually into working in, in a union. And how was that experience?

222
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:52,000
Well, that was an experience. That was another thing to learn. I worked in the Northern Pennsylvania on a union drive there.

223
00:27:53,000 --> 00:28:10,000
And then eventually we left the UE and I went to work in 69 for 1199, which was a civil rights related union, the hospital workers.

224
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:30,000
And the interesting thing about the union basically was a progressive union and was built among African American workers in the hospital service workers in New York, dietary housekeeping, nursing assistance, et cetera.

225
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:39,000
And we worked on establishing the union in Pennsylvania where it was not majority black situation.

226
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:56,000
And amazingly enough, we found that we were able to build a union even in vast majority white hospitals, not in Pittsburgh, but the first one that we won was in Louis Town, which was almost all white.

227
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:05,000
And that was against a campaign by the employer for that this was a black union and all of that was happening.

228
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:16,000
That was an interesting experience. We were able to build the union in rural areas in Pennsylvania.

229
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:24,000
And how are rural areas of Pennsylvania in terms of their race relations?

230
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:36,000
Well, I don't know. I don't know. I worked in Wilkesbury where we organized the registered nurses and all of the whole hospital.

231
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:48,000
That was one of the early ones. And that was Mercy Hospital in Wilkesbury.

232
00:29:48,000 --> 00:30:00,000
I remember they campaigned against the union by saying that the nurses are professionals and we've worked hard to come away from being called cold crackers.

233
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:11,000
And of course that made the nurses live it because their fathers had sent them to nursing school on a co-minor salary.

234
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:27,000
So we won there. We won there and in Butler, I can't think of the other towns. Spangler, Huntington, Washington,

235
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:39,000
Pennsylvania, Cannonburg, or hospitals where in the not big cities, but more rural areas where we were a part of the union.

236
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:50,000
The rest of the union was African-American in Baltimore. Baltimore was one of the first, I think one of the first outside of New York City.

237
00:30:50,000 --> 00:31:03,000
I remember Carretta King went there and helped the campaign. And Johns Hopkins was organized into 1199. That was probably 69 or 70.

238
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:16,000
And then there was an 1199 campaign in Charleston, South Carolina. And around the same time, or a little bit earlier than that I think.

239
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:27,000
And they were not able to win union recognition. But there was a huge battle. But they didn't break it down.

240
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:42,000
There was some kind of a settlement that they would allow the union to collect dues or something. It didn't build the basis for establishing the union in the South.

241
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:59,000
And it's still unorganized. And of course, Kentucky, the hospital workers are almost all unorganized. I mean, it's very, very hard to do that in the Southern states.

242
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:08,000
I think they would once foster and they want to change this and be good.

243
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:10,000
Okay, well, they would treat well.

244
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:18,000
This is just a side, but I've done a bunch of work in Southwest Georgia with the SNCC folks down there and Charles Sherrod.

245
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:29,000
Yeah. And he, one of the reason he admitted to me, one of the reasons that he went to, you know, went north to seminary was to recruit people to come down.

246
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:32,000
And part of what he needed was vehicle.

247
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:36,000
But you're starting to say, are we?

248
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:41,000
Great. I was asking about, we mentioned off camera just for a second.

249
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:46,000
And we were talking about the importance of high wind air and I was talking about it being in a rather remote place.

250
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:49,000
And you were starting to talk about how people got around in those days.

251
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:54,000
Oh, well, I wonder, during that period, it was in Knoxville.

252
00:32:54,000 --> 00:33:03,000
You know, I, it was earlier, you know, where it was burned down. I think that was in Monegal, Tennessee.

253
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:05,000
And you're so on. Right.

254
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:11,000
It was in a big house in Knoxville at the time when we were going.

255
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:14,000
And I think it's somewhere else now. I haven't been there.

256
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:15,000
Yeah.

257
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:17,000
But I think Newmarket or somewhere.

258
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:27,000
Although I have been back, I went back because my friend who I work with on single payer is from Tennessee and he invited us back.

259
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:32,000
And he had to play about Miles Horton and Don West.

260
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:37,000
And that was somewhere near that area.

261
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:42,000
And we went to the grave of Miles Horton.

262
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:47,000
And I saw where the school had originally been.

263
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:50,000
I have a picture of Walter and me with the marker.

264
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:53,000
You know, there's a historical marker there.

265
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:54,000
In Monegal.

266
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:56,000
It's in Knoxville. Yeah.

267
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:58,000
Interesting.

268
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:09,000
Which leads me to ask the question too. I mean, the work that you were doing with the nurses union, in which you clearly saw as civil rights activity,

269
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:11,000
did the nurses see it that way?

270
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:14,000
And then, and what other, or the, or the hospital workers?

271
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:19,000
And who, who were your allies in working on these campaigns?

272
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:24,000
Did some of the other civil rights organizations support you or not?

273
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:25,000
Yeah. Yeah.

274
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:38,000
I remember, well, in Pittsburgh, when we first started in, you know, 69, the other unions were not sympathetic because here was a union.

275
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:40,000
It was a New York-based union.

276
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:47,000
And, you know, we had organized a petition from some hospital workers to ask them to come and help us.

277
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:51,000
And they were all excited about, you know, coming.

278
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:54,000
So they came and put me onto the staff.

279
00:34:54,000 --> 00:35:02,000
But the other unions in the city were not sympathetic because they saw it as their territory.

280
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:06,000
But the allies were the UE was very sympathetic.

281
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:13,000
And David Montgomery, at the time, was a professor at the University of Pittsburgh.

282
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:24,000
And he, he and the guy from Tom Quinn, from the United Electrical Workers, headed up the support committee for us.

283
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:38,000
Because at the time in 1969 and 1970, there were, there were the national revelations law did not cover hospital workers.

284
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:53,000
And therefore, you know, to get recognition, you had to really build, you know, a movement that had some strategy of forcing the hospital on moral or grounds to,

285
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:58,000
to recognize the union, which is what they had done in New York.

286
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:02,000
You know, they had more power there and they got Rockefeller to back it.

287
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:05,000
And, you know, they were able to do it.

288
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:10,000
We were not able to win in, in 70.

289
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:13,000
There was a strike at Presbyterian Hospital.

290
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:17,000
And we were not able to, you know, gain collective bargaining.

291
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:23,000
But as a result of this strike, the governor of Pennsylvania at that time, his name was Shaap.

292
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:31,000
And they were contemplating, collective bargaining for state employees at the time.

293
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:35,000
And as a result of that strike, they added hospital workers.

294
00:36:35,000 --> 00:36:46,000
So Pennsylvania became a state that included under state law the right for hospital workers to organize.

295
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:52,000
And it was not until 1975, I think it was 75.

296
00:36:52,000 --> 00:37:06,000
I think that's right, that the NLRB was amended its coverage and made it possible to organize in hospitals across the country.

297
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:12,000
But so our movement was a part of, you know, opening that door and making that happen.

298
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:15,000
What were the racial demographics among hospital workers?

299
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:19,000
Were there a majority of African Americans in the field?

300
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:30,000
Well, in, in, in, in, in, in Pittsburgh, probably 30% or 40% were African-American.

301
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:36,000
Among the service workers, I mean, we weren't organizing in among the nurses in Pittsburgh.

302
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:39,000
I mean, we couldn't reach them.

303
00:37:39,000 --> 00:37:42,000
But it wasn't majority.

304
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:47,000
It wasn't like you could just unite African-American workers.

305
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:51,000
And then you had majority, which I think is how it was in New York.

306
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:55,000
So it was a new, a new, a new challenge.

307
00:37:55,000 --> 00:38:00,000
But, you know, I think that's something we were proud of was that we did build the union.

308
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:05,000
That other hospital workers called on us, people from Union Town called.

309
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:13,000
We started a movement there and people were all related to coal miners and had a union tradition in their families.

310
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:15,000
And didn't care.

311
00:38:15,000 --> 00:38:18,000
They wanted a union, you know.

312
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:22,000
There was a strike in Union Town as well, also, which was not won.

313
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:25,000
But was a valiant effort.

314
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:31,000
It was amazing that in Union Town is a part of that effort.

315
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:38,000
You had to strike for a ignition because before the law, you couldn't get an election.

316
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:45,000
You had no way to gain, no established way to gain collective bargaining rights.

317
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:51,000
So I remember there's a part of the effort to get the hospital to settle.

318
00:38:51,000 --> 00:38:59,000
The work we would go out to the various enterprises of the people who were on the board of the hospital.

319
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:02,000
And somebody from the coal mine was there.

320
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:09,000
So we could close down the coal mine, close down the clothing factory,

321
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:11,000
close down anything.

322
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:19,000
And the city, except the hospital, was still functioning because it wasn't a solid strike.

323
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:22,000
And that was what happened in Pittsburgh as well.

324
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:25,000
It wasn't a solid majority that went out.

325
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:28,000
But it did. We did win.

326
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:37,000
We won the first union that was established was at the Jewish Home and Hospital for the age in Pittsburgh.

327
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:40,000
And it was a lovely campaign.

328
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:44,000
That was a majority African American workers.

329
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:52,000
And that campaign was led by Henry Nicholas, who's now the head of the hospital workers, Union and Philadelphia.

330
00:39:52,000 --> 00:40:02,000
But before the Philadelphia Union was established, you know, Nicholas came to help us in the Pittsburgh area.

331
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:09,000
And this was an area where clearly the civil rights movement was a part of people's thinking.

332
00:40:09,000 --> 00:40:13,000
And very responsive to that.

333
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:19,000
And since we didn't get a vote, but we had a clear majority, we had a sit-in.

334
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:25,000
It was on Christmas Eve in 1969.

335
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:29,000
And we were, it was solid.

336
00:40:29,000 --> 00:40:33,000
It was an amazingly strong movement.

337
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:42,000
And we were sitting there and told management, you know, if there were any emergencies, we would send someone to help.

338
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:47,000
But other than that, you know, and the woman from the laundry kept coming through and said,

339
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:49,000
we had to be done.

340
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:53,000
We said that wasn't an emergency. They could go with that.

341
00:40:53,000 --> 00:41:01,000
And by the end of the day, we had an agreement with the management that they would conduct an election.

342
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:08,000
We found a rabbi from Rodolf Shalom, who was going to hold this election.

343
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:15,000
And we had a date set for sometime in January or February that we would have a secret ballot election.

344
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:21,000
And an agreement that if a majority voted for it, they would recognize the union in bargain.

345
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:25,000
Yeah, that was our big, that's really why we could establish the union there.

346
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:28,000
Because we finally won something.

347
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:34,000
And that met that we had a, you know, we had several hundred, I can't remember how many it was.

348
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:39,000
A couple of hundred members there at that nursing home.

349
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:43,000
And that was the beginning of the union in Pennsylvania.

350
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:50,000
But it was shortly after that that they passed the law in 70 or 71.

351
00:41:50,000 --> 00:42:02,000
And then we began winning under the law, under the state law in Louistown and Wilkes-Farry in 73 in Washington.

352
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:06,000
And you know, a number of other hospitals. And built the union.

353
00:42:06,000 --> 00:42:28,000
And many of those bargaining units were majority-wide, which something we're proud of that, you know, gave your hope that you could unite people on economic issues with some understanding of civil rights issues and make a common fight for justice within the country.

354
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:49,000
Now, as you brought people together to form the unions and brought the communities together, did that ever lead communities create unity within those communities that led them on to other issues to fight other kinds of battles that you know.

355
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:54,000
I don't know. I'm sorry.

356
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:17,000
I don't know. I mean, I think that in general, we built solidarity for other workers, you know, so that we would demonstrate with other unions or other people trying to get the union or, you know,

357
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:21,000
bring people together around those issues.

358
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:29,000
Great. Now I was just curious about how empowering it is to take on other issues.

359
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:46,000
Okay. So how did, you know, we started by talking about your family. How did your family back home respond to the work that you've had decided to devote yourself to?

360
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:51,000
Well, they were not happy about it.

361
00:43:51,000 --> 00:44:03,000
My mother mainly because I had left school before I graduated. I didn't finally graduate from college until 67.

362
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:13,000
So I had left before my last semester and my mother was very upset about that.

363
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:24,000
It was that and also concern about it was dangerous, you know, and they were not happy about it at all.

364
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:39,000
So it was difficult because it was not the norm that had been planned.

365
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:52,000
Well, even Walter's parents who had much more understanding about the movement were frightened about the situation and worried about that.

366
00:44:52,000 --> 00:45:00,000
And then, you know, there were other problems about movement people. I remember, you know, we were also involved in the anti-war movement.

367
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:10,000
And in the days of the anti-war movement, I mean it was terrible what would happen. The FBI went to see my parents about this.

368
00:45:10,000 --> 00:45:26,000
So that doesn't help the situation where they were questioned and, you know, they didn't have, you know, anyway, any context in which to place that.

369
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:35,000
So, you know, it created a great deal of difficulty. They were questioned about, you know, the picket lines against the Vietnam War.

370
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:39,000
And then, do you remember them getting in touch with you and telling you what happened?

371
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:44,000
Yes, I remember, you know, my mother crying on the phone and I'm trying to explain.

372
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:53,000
And the FBI has just left their house and been questioning them. And, you know, they think that I'm, you know, in some kind of terrible trouble.

373
00:45:53,000 --> 00:46:04,000
And that the, you know, they never had run-ins with the law, you know, they, they, that was completely different to them.

374
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:16,000
And of course, that was what it was about. They were trying to repress, you know, make it difficult for people to participate in such a movement.

375
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:22,000
And did you see the various things that you were involved in, like the anti-war movement, but also the Louis Vuorgonizing Civil Rights?

376
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:25,000
Did you see this as all of a piece or a separate?

377
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:40,000
Yeah, I saw it as all connected. For me, it was the same folks that, you know, they were the same people that were concerned about the same issues.

378
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:49,000
I think that the Civil Rights Movement was the foundation of the ability of people to do the other organizing.

379
00:46:49,000 --> 00:47:09,000
I think that that was the catalyst and the strength and the momentum. That was the powerful movement that really changed the country, made it totally different, and made it possible for people to do these, these other kinds of things.

380
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:38,000
It was, you know, what was out there in front and with the moral compulsion and made it possible for the Civil Rights Movement, the anti-war movement, all of the other kinds of things that followed were grounded in and took their strength from, you know, they were connected to the civil rights movement.

381
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:43,000
It was connected to what the Civil Rights Movement had done.

382
00:47:43,000 --> 00:48:04,000
The power of common people moving together is very compelling and gives you all kinds of ideas about what you might change, you know, seeing a Fannie Lou Hamer, I saw her many times.

383
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:30,000
And knowing her story of what she had been through, where does a person gain that strength, you know, where does that come from that someone of such humble origins could give such leadership that really shook the nation and changed it.

384
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:51,000
I mean, she changed that, you know, that convention, you know, when she said, we didn't come all this way for two seats, you know, that a woman from that background could say that, you say, my goodness, doesn't take, you know, you don't have to be Einstein.

385
00:48:51,000 --> 00:49:07,000
You can, you know, that we have within the nation, many people, many people, all kinds of people who could become movers to make things happen differently in the country.

386
00:49:07,000 --> 00:49:11,000
And capable of creating extraordinary change.

387
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:32,000
Yes, and that really, the whole Civil Rights Movement was that way, you know, it really was about people who had fewer resources on which, you know, to rely.

388
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:41,000
But so much strength in that movement, I mean, you think about the freedom writers.

389
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:58,000
I'll never forget the Diana Nash story, you know, when she's called by the Justice Department, she says, they say, you know, you can't do this, you can't pick up this ride, you can be killed.

390
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:07,000
And she says, we know that, we are aware, we have all made out our wills.

391
00:50:07,000 --> 00:50:10,000
Yeah, that's just powerful.

392
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:21,000
And that was there on a massive basis, not just one or two or three leaders, but many, many, many, many people.

393
00:50:21,000 --> 00:50:25,000
So that changed the country.

394
00:50:25,000 --> 00:50:36,000
And I think propelled the other movements that have been asking or asserting their rights within the country as well.

395
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:41,000
Did you ever personally interact with the women's movement?

396
00:50:41,000 --> 00:50:46,000
I was involved in the pay equity.

397
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:55,000
And Coalition of Labor Union Women, I was the president in Pittsburgh of the Coalition of Labor Union Women.

398
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:58,000
And we carried on quite a bit.

399
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:00,000
What kind of things did you work on?

400
00:51:00,000 --> 00:51:10,000
Well, it was a time when Labor Union Women didn't have any role at all and the officialdom, you know.

401
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:19,000
I remember so many times I would get up to speak at the Alleghenies Central Labor Council and couldn't get recognition, you know.

402
00:51:19,000 --> 00:51:25,000
Or they would say it wasn't the right time on the agenda to raise that issue.

403
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:27,000
I mean, it was difficult.

404
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:36,000
So the Coalition of Labor Union Women, which was founded in 74, kind of.

405
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:39,000
I was just taking it.

406
00:51:39,000 --> 00:51:43,000
So the Coalition of Labor Union Women was formed in 1974.

407
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:46,000
The Coalition of Labor Union Women was founded in 1974.

408
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:49,000
I went to the founding. I think we were in Detroit.

409
00:51:49,000 --> 00:51:51,000
I'm not sure where we were.

410
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:53,000
Those hotels all looked the same.

411
00:51:53,000 --> 00:52:03,000
But it gave us a way for union women to form an organization and to speak on behalf of, you know, women's issues, whatever.

412
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:05,000
So that's kind of what we did.

413
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:14,000
A number of chapters include became kind of the focal point of women who were concerned about civil rights and anti-war as well as union issues.

414
00:52:14,000 --> 00:52:24,000
And we had a dynamic chapter in Pittsburgh and they were always telling us we were getting out of line.

415
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:28,000
But it was a good thing.

416
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:34,000
I think about not being recognized, but I imagine that that must have been terribly frustrating at times given what we were doing.

417
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:39,000
Well, just funny memories of the way things were.

418
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:41,000
I mean, I love the labor movement.

419
00:52:41,000 --> 00:52:47,000
But when you know it, you know all of its problems as well.

420
00:52:47,000 --> 00:52:51,000
That was one of its difficulties.

421
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:54,000
Some progress has been made on that.

422
00:52:54,000 --> 00:52:58,000
You know, there are big problems within the labor movement.

423
00:52:58,000 --> 00:53:03,000
We have so much to do, so many workers unorganized.

424
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:14,000
And so we're losing ground in terms of wages compared to where all the money is going to the top.

425
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:19,000
And you're still working in the movement.

426
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:27,000
Yeah, I worked on the, trying to build the union, the nurses union here in Louisville.

427
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:33,000
But right now I'm working on the single payer movement.

428
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:47,000
You know, the effort to finally win in our nation, universal health care, to make health care a right for every person and to win a system where we would publicly fund it.

429
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:59,000
So that we would remove the economic barriers to getting care and make certain that everyone could get care, regardless of ability to pay.

430
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:04,000
And that's the effort now that I'm working on.

431
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:16,000
There's a billing congress called HR676 sponsored by the wonderful congressman, John Connors, who also introduced the,

432
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:22,000
the Martin Luther King holiday bill and has led many.

433
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:30,000
He introduced the shorter work week, which we worked with him back in a while back decades ago.

434
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:45,000
But he has introduced this bill, which would remove the private for-profit insurance industry from our health care system and remove the for-profit hospitals so that it wouldn't.

435
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:48,000
You couldn't profit here in health care.

436
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:55,000
You could earn a living if you worked, but you couldn't make profit from denying care.

437
00:54:55,000 --> 00:54:59,000
And of course, that's the system that we have now.

438
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:13,000
And I'm hopeful that the issue of health care unites people because it touches all of us and that it may be a place where we can break through.

439
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:31,000
And once again, learn how to make do big, important things instead of just talking as though it's only possible to get tiny, tiny, tiny incremental change because nothing else is politically feasible.

440
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:40,000
Of course, from my background, I know that with masses of people in motion, you can change it.

441
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:47,000
So that's what we're working to build that movement that makes it possible to pass that bill.

442
00:55:47,000 --> 00:55:52,000
It seems that there are a few things that shouldn't be run as businesses.

443
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:58,000
Health care, education, the military, even, are not, should not be run as businesses.

444
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:05,000
Could you speak to that issue or do you think that we have to go smaller steps before we get to that?

445
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:11,000
I'm not thinking about small. I think we should step as big as we can.

446
00:56:11,000 --> 00:56:31,000
And I agree with that. I mean, I think that, you know, I'm tremendously concerned about the direction of education because I think public schools are being undermined by these charter for profits, you know, privatization of our education.

447
00:56:31,000 --> 00:56:48,000
I was really cheering for those wonderful Chicago teachers who took that on and who built the bonds between the community and the parents and the needs of the children and the teachers,

448
00:56:48,000 --> 00:57:03,000
as all on the same side and wanting to have, you know, a way to teach and also a way that people could aren't a living by teaching without being, you know, so kicked around.

449
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:10,000
And I agree that on the military, on these subcontracting in the military, it's terrible and the wars are terrible too.

450
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:39,000
I don't know, it's one, because I'd worked, you know, with all these healthcare workers, I became aware, you know, working with nurses here in Louisville of the profit motive was understaffing these nursing units so that, you know, we always said that even the most excellent nurse can be overworked to the point of incompetence.

451
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:48,000
Certainly true, and of course, if you're, you know, these hospitals at the time were owned by Humana, which was a profit-making company.

452
00:57:48,000 --> 00:58:08,000
And so, of course, they staffed as slim as they could. And that meant that there wasn't enough of the nurse to give to all of the patients and patient care suffers, of course, since then we've, you know, nurses knew it all along, but since then they've done some studies that show, you know, deaths and infections

453
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:29,000
and all of those things rise when the nurse staffing goes down in relationship to the numbers of patients. So anyway, it should not be a for-profit business and it needs to be run in the interest of patient care and of wellness and prevention and John Connors.

454
00:58:29,000 --> 00:58:46,000
I am proud. He's introduced this bill. It was first introduced in 2003 and we've been working to build the movement around it and I picked up on the issue around to build union support because I think that that's a key.

455
00:58:46,000 --> 00:59:03,000
We need the union support to make it happen. So, we started building the All Unions Committee for Single Pay or Health Care, HR676. And the first group I got to endorse it was my Clue chapter and the Chicago Clue chapter.

456
00:59:03,000 --> 00:59:16,000
And then we got the national Clue to endorse it, the Coalition of Labor Union Women. And then we got friends who were in the Coalition of Black Trade Unionists and they took it to their convention.

457
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:30,000
So with those two union groups, we began to try to get other unions. And at this point, we have gotten, these are endorsements of HR676, the Connors Bill.

458
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:56,000
We have 605 unions that have endorsed that bill. 43 state AFLCIO federations. And 146 Central Labor Councils. And I think 22 of the international unions and we're still working on it because we're still not there.

459
00:59:56,000 --> 01:00:10,000
The bill that was passed doesn't solve the problem of bringing care to everyone, nor of cutting the costs. And so many people can't get care because they can't pay.

460
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:22,000
Even many who have insurance can't pay the copays and deductibles are their barriers to the ability to get care.

461
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:34,000
You know, the country has adopted this insurance company thinking that our problem is so costly is because people are using the system.

462
01:00:34,000 --> 01:00:49,000
And it isn't the reason at all. The fact is that people in countries that pay half as much per capita as we do for healthcare, they have more days in the hospital, more doctors office visits, etc.

463
01:00:49,000 --> 01:01:02,000
So the problem is that people are utilizing the healthcare. That's an insurance company way of thinking if anyone uses it, they're losing money. So the job is to put barriers up so they won't go.

464
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:18,000
So I think we're winning on that too. I mean, we're a ways away. And there are lots of people who say, OK, that just isn't politically feasible. You have to set your sights on something lower.

465
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:39,000
And I say, but something lower won't solve the problem. And the job is to bring universal healthcare to our people. And of course that would do so much in terms of the disparity between African Americans and whites in this country.

466
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:54,000
If we could at least get that right. And you know, the fight for healthcare has the amazing ability to do that. I just became aware recently that in 65 when Medicare was passed.

467
01:01:54,000 --> 01:02:10,000
And all of a sudden all these seniors had money to pay for hospitalizations. They wrote into the law that the hospital couldn't get money if they were a segregated hospital.

468
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:32,000
So all of a sudden the hospitals of the South, they're integrated because they couldn't get the money. And here was federal money that was available to them. So I mean, we can change all kinds of things with healthcare if we can make certain that everybody has a right to get that.

469
01:02:32,000 --> 01:02:43,000
And I'm aware of the studies. They're just awful. I looked at a study by David Satcher. You know, he was.

470
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:59,000
Search in general and someone who was here in Louisville, Ottawa, a troutman. And I don't know what year the study is. But the study said, I think it was that there were 83,000.

471
01:02:59,000 --> 01:03:13,000
And access deaths in the African American community. Desk that would not have occurred had there been equality. And of course that's related to the healthcare system.

472
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:40,000
Other things too, but a large part to the lack of access to healthcare. And it's just a crime. And I'm hopeful that we'll find a way to build the movement that can change that. And that maybe in the doing, we might stimulate open some other doors to end the wars and to win justice.

473
01:03:40,000 --> 01:04:09,000
And to win back the voting rights that are now threatened. And you know, it seems to me you have to go forward or you'll go backward. And I think we face that now. And certainly within the labor union movement and the voting rights decision is just heartbreaking. And we have to get ourselves together and and refight that battle.

474
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:18,000
How do you carry on? I mean, you personally in terms of what are your sources of strength to keep to keep fighting?

475
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:32,000
Well, I have a husband. That helps a lot. You know, he's kind of amazing at his ability to keep to keep going.

476
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:58,000
And even stronger than I am, I think in many ways. And I've learned a lot from him, you know, he came from a different perspective on all of this. People laugh, you know. He hasn't lost his New York accent. So he still sounds like he just walked out of the Bronx.

477
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:12,000
And I don't know, maybe I sound like I just walked out of Paduca. And we never picked up each other. Sometimes we don't even know, you know, what word you're saying. Could you repeat that? Try to get it together.

478
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:29,000
I think lots of couples met in the South, I think, you know, during that period of time when we all kind of got mixed up and lifted up in a major way, lifted by a movement.

479
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:47,000
You know, that was happening around it through which we learned. I mean, you know, I would say I gained more from the movement than I gave because when I walked into it, I didn't know what to give or how to give. I was just there.

480
01:05:47,000 --> 01:06:07,000
But we all learned and became better people and were knowledgeable about what others had done before us and what could be done and what needed to be done within our country. So we've been working on it.

481
01:06:07,000 --> 01:06:22,000
One thing I think is interesting is, you know, obviously the movement didn't have a pension plan. So now you've got, you know, people who devoted their lives to the movement are, you know, either place in their lives where for some people that we've talked to, they're really struggling.

482
01:06:22,000 --> 01:06:51,000
Yeah, I'm sure. Well, see from the point at which I went to work for the union movement, I was had a fairly regular income and pension. But I know many people are in that kind of a situation. Well, we need to expand social security because quite frankly, many people who had good pension plans in the auto industry or the steel industry or everyone who had a pension plan.

483
01:06:52,000 --> 01:07:21,000
But where else? It's all under threat now. I mean, those pension plans are going under people are getting a small percentage and social security is inadequate to do it. So, which is why we've been working on a resolution to the AFFL CIO for the upcoming convention that says, protect social security and Medicare and the way in which you do that is that, you know,

484
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:50,000
social security is that social security, we need to expand the tax so that it doesn't cut off at 100,000 or whatever that figure is so that all wages are taxed. So it's not a regressive tax and that capital gains and interest is taxed as well. And that that will certainly save social security and allow us to enhance the benefits and that Medicare will be saved if we put everyone into the money.

485
01:07:51,000 --> 01:08:11,000
So, we need to do that for the next month and that's the same Medicare and that's the expanded and improved Medicare for all, which is the single payer plan, HR676, introduced by Congressmen Conniors, that both of those can be saved and that calls on the AFL CIO to call for a March on Washington to promote these causes.

486
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:40,000
Well, we got eight Central Labor Councils descended in that resolution and I think people agree with that. I don't think that we have things in motion to where people are thinking bigger, but they're going to have to start doing that because we can't just hang on, we can't even hang on to what we have unless we start moving people.

487
01:08:40,000 --> 01:09:00,000
So, I think that's a very important thing to try to improve what we have. I think there's a tremendous effort to use immigrants now and much the way they used to use African Americans to try to divide people.

488
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:13,000
I think that's a very important anti-immigrant movement, but I think we can win people there too. To be... that's part of what's in the Conniors Bill is that it doesn't exclude anybody.

489
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:34,000
The Affordable Care Act says, if you don't have a legal document, you can't even buy insurance. So anyway, basically, we take the money that immigrant workers who are undocumented pay and to Medicare and Social Security.

490
01:09:34,000 --> 01:09:44,000
They never get it back because they're not able to collect on those benefits.

491
01:09:44,000 --> 01:09:51,000
I actually think we might... Sure.

492
01:09:51,000 --> 01:10:02,000
How do you... One of the things that love struggling is the number of African Americans in the U.S. and the American people who are being prosecuted on that?

493
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:14,000
Well, I would agree that it's very troubling. I'm not particularly knowledgeable. I know that the numbers have increased tremendously.

494
01:10:14,000 --> 01:10:31,000
I was happy to see that the judge in... I guess she's in New York. She's in that district throughout the stop in Frisk and that there is... people are raising this issue.

495
01:10:31,000 --> 01:11:00,000
It's very troubling that there are so many African Americans in prison and we need to do something to change that situation. Clearly, many of them are innocent or are sentenced far beyond what is deserved for whatever they committed.

496
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:23,000
It's terrible. The way the nation has decided to deal with the problems of joblessness and disruption of families and lives in communities where we have huge unemployment levels which has a terrible impact.

497
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:35,000
We don't have equality and education so that we're opening the doors for a healthier life. It's a terrible problem.

498
01:11:35,000 --> 01:11:48,000
I wish I knew exactly what we could do. I'm ready to work on it because I think it really is a huge problem.

499
01:11:48,000 --> 01:12:05,000
This has been a remarkable interview, especially underlining the centrality of economic justice to the movement. I want to ask you if there is something I didn't ask or I should have asked or anything that you'd like to add at this point. Any questions you are expecting?

500
01:12:05,000 --> 01:12:26,000
No, I appreciate the opportunity to talk about this. I haven't thought about many of these things for a very long time but I'm glad you're doing this and I'm sure you have other people who played much more prominent roles.

501
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:44,000
I mean I think that's something that's really come out of the project strongly is what a movement is made of right or all the people doing their pieces and how it's all they all connect.

502
01:12:44,000 --> 01:12:53,000
Thank you.

503
01:12:53,000 --> 01:13:07,000
I had fun, I don't know whether you know I probably should have thought more about this has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

